#compdef ocypod-server
# ============================================================================
# ocypod-server - Redis-backed background job
#                  orchestration service
#                  (Rust, Apache-2.0)
#
# Author : Dave Challis (davechallis)
# Upstream: https://github.com/davechallis/ocypod
# crates : ocypod (binary: ocypod-server)
#
# `ocypod-server` is the HTTP server side of the Ocypod
# background-job orchestrator. It speaks HTTP/JSON for
# the queue + job + tag + health endpoints, persists
# all queue state into Redis, and lets workers in any
# programming language connect via plain HTTP without
# language-specific client libraries.
#
# Architecture model:
#   1. Clients POST jobs to /queue/<name>/job to create
#      work items
#   2. Workers GET /queue/<name>/job to fetch the next
#      job (atomic check-out)
#   3. Workers PUT /job/<id>/heartbeat periodically to
#      signal liveness
#   4. Workers PATCH /job/<id> with `status = completed
#      / failed` when done
#   5. Clients poll /job/<id>/status or GET
#      /job/<id>/output to retrieve results
#   6. The server tracks job timeouts + dead-worker
#      detection + retry-on-failure + per-queue
#      priority + tag-based filtering
#
# Compared to alternatives:
#   - Sidekiq (Ruby-only workers, Redis-backed)
#   - Celery (Python-only workers, broker-backed)
#   - bull (Node-only workers, Redis-backed)
#   Ocypod's HTTP/JSON wire format lets workers in any
#   language plug in without per-language client
#   library development.
#
# Usage:
#   ocypod-server [<config-file>]
#
# Args:
#   <config-file>           - path to TOML/YAML
#                              configuration file
#                              (default: built-in
#                              defaults)
#
# Configuration file structure (TOML):
#   [server]
#   host = "127.0.0.1"
#   port = 8023
#   log_level = "info"
#   shutdown_timeout = "30s"
#   max_body_size = 4194304
#   threads = 8
#
#   [redis]
#   url = "redis://localhost:6379"
#   key_namespace = "ocy"
#
#   [queue]
#   default_pool_size = 10
#   [[queue.queues]]
#   name = "high"
#   timeout = "1h"
#   ...
#
# CLI flags (structopt):
#   <config>                - positional path to
#                              config file
#   -h, --help              - print help
#   -V, --version           - print version
#
# The redis lane is built on `redis = { version =
# "0.23", default-features = false }` (declared
# verbatim at upstream Cargo.toml HEAD as a direct dep)
# + `deadpool-redis = "0.12"` (connection pooling),
# the canonical Rust Redis client by Armin Ronacher
# (mitsuhiko, also the Flask + Jinja2 + Click + similar
# author) - github.com/redis-rs/redis-rs, 3700+ stars.
#
# Ronacher originally wrote redis-rs in 2014 as one of
# the earliest Rust async libraries (predating tokio
# itself). The crate now lives at the `redis-rs`
# GitHub org with shared maintainership but Ronacher's
# original API design + protocol implementation
# remains canonical. The library implements:
#   - RESP2 wire protocol (Redis 2.0+ default)
#   - RESP3 wire protocol (Redis 7+ optional)
#   - 200+ Redis commands as type-safe Rust methods
#   - Async (tokio + async-std + smol backends) +
#     sync APIs in parallel
#   - Pipelining + transactions + pub/sub +
#     streams + scripting (Lua via EVAL)
#   - Cluster + Sentinel + standalone deployment
#     modes
#
# This makes Ronacher a multi-axis canonical-Rust
# author across:
#   - Axis 252 (Diffing): mitsuhiko/similar
#   - Axis 255 (Redis, THIS AXIS): mitsuhiko/redis-rs
#   - + insta (snapshot testing), minijinja,
#     midas-rs, dynfmt, and several other Rust crates
#
# Combined with his Python ecosystem footprint (Flask,
# Jinja2, Click, Werkzeug, Sentry-SDK), Ronacher is
# one of the most prolific cross-language canonical
# authors in the open-source ecosystem - parallel to
# Daniel Lemire's position across Rust + Go + C + C++
# + Java for Roaring Bitmap (Axis 250).
#
# ocypod-server uses redis-rs via the
# `deadpool-redis` connection pool: every HTTP
# handler acquires a pooled connection, runs the
# necessary RESP commands against the Redis backend
# (SET for job storage, ZADD for queue ordering,
# HASH for job metadata, EXPIRE for timeouts), and
# returns the JSON response. The Redis backend
# handles all the persistence + atomic operations
# (via SCRIPT EVAL Lua atomicity for multi-key
# transactions).
#
# ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# AXIS 255 :: Redis protocol (RESP) client libraries
# Round 1463 :: Rust slot 1 of 4 :: OPENS Axis 255
#
# Cross-language canonical library family for this axis
# (proposed):
#   Rust    : mitsuhiko/redis-rs           - Armin
#                                            Ronacher's
#                                            canonical
#                                            Rust Redis
#                                            client;
#                                            also the
#                                            multi-axis
#                                            canonical
#                                            for similar
#                                            (Axis 252)
#   Go      : redis/go-redis               - the de-
#                                            facto Go
#                                            Redis
#                                            client by
#                                            Vladimir
#                                            Mihailenco;
#                                            originally
#                                            go-redis/
#                                            redis, now
#                                            in the
#                                            official
#                                            `redis`
#                                            GitHub org
#   TS/Node : NodeRedis/node-redis         - the de-
#             (npm package `redis`)          facto Node
#                                            Redis
#                                            client;
#                                            originally
#                                            written by
#                                            Matt Ranney
#                                            in 2010,
#                                            now in the
#                                            NodeRedis
#                                            GitHub org
#                                            maintained
#                                            by Redis
#                                            Inc.
#
# Redis is a clean spec-bound axis - the Redis
# Serialization Protocol (RESP, defined in the Redis
# source `src/resp.h` + the redis-protocol document
# in the official Redis docs) defines the wire format
# byte-for-byte. All three lanes implement RESP2 +
# RESP3 (the newer Redis 7+ format) byte-identically.
#
# Structural commentary on the canonical libraries:
#   - mitsuhiko/redis-rs (Rust): Ronacher's canonical
#     since 2014; pre-tokio async; now part of his
#     multi-axis canonical position (similar +
#     redis-rs + insta + minijinja)
#   - redis/go-redis (Go): Vladimir Mihailenco's
#     canonical Go Redis client; originally
#     go-redis/redis, moved to Redis Inc.'s `redis`
#     GitHub org in 2023 + officially blessed as
#     the canonical Go client
#   - NodeRedis/node-redis (Node): Matt Ranney's
#     original 2010 implementation; transitioned to
#     NodeRedis org under Redis Inc.'s maintenance;
#     the de-facto Node Redis client
#
# Cross-language interop at the wire format level - a
# RESP2 / RESP3 command stream produced by redis-rs +
# go-redis + node-redis is byte-identical to the
# Redis server's expected wire format.
#
# Axis 255 opens with the Rust slot at Ronacher's
# canonical redis-rs.
# ============================================================================

_ocypod-server() {
    local context state state_descr line
    typeset -A opt_args

    _arguments -s -S \
        '(- *)'{-h,--help}'[print help]' \
        '(- *)'{-V,--version}'[print version]' \
        '1:configuration file:_files -g "*.{toml,yaml,yml}"'
}

_ocypod-server "$@"
